  "prompt": "How do you determine the unit of quantity of electricity?",
  "response": "The unit of quantity of electricity is the coulomb. It is a standard unit in the International System of Units (SI). \n\n1. **Definition**: One coulomb is defined as the amount of electric charge transported by a constant current of one ampere in one second. \n\n2. **Relation to other quantities**:\n   - **Current (I)**: Measured in amperes (A), where 1 ampere is defined as 1 coulomb per second.\n   - **Time (t)**: Measured in seconds (s).\n\nThe relationship can be expressed as:\n\\[\nQ = I \\times t\n\\]\nwhere \\(Q\\) is the quantity of electricity in coulombs, \\(I\\) is the current in amperes, and \\(t\\) is the time in seconds.\n\n3. **Other Units**: \n   - In practical contexts, it is often useful to use larger or smaller units of charge, such as milliCoulombs (mC), microCoulombs (\u00b5C), and so on, where:\n     - \\(1 \\text{ mC} = 10^{-3} \\text{ C}\\)\n     - \\(1 \\text{ \u00b5C} = 10^{-6} \\text{ C}\\)\n\n4. **Applications**: The coulomb is used in various fields including physics and engineering, especially in the study of electric circuits, electrostatics, and more.\n\nIn summary, the coulomb is the foundational unit for measuring electric charge, which can be calculated using the current and time.",
